<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Bourses unimpressed by dollar
intervention
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Central bank intervention in support of the dollar was unable to rescue
bourses yesterday afternoon, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT wrote an unsettled and gloomy end to the official week, down 2.2
per cent and closing with the Dax index 16.79 lower at 2,005.31.
There was a brief recovery later, but the Ibis-indicated Dax subsided again
to close at 2,005.07. 'Currency intervention never lasts,' said a broker.
'It's an emergency signal, a bit of a panic measure, and it shows that
something is radically wrong.'
Turnover fell from DM9.2bn to DM7bn. Activity was dominated by another sharp
fall in Deutsche Bank, which ended DM18.20 lower at DM669.80, after DM663,
down 8.5 per cent on the week.
The stock's outlook has been clouded by investor worries about the bank's
exposure to volatile debt markets and recent property scandals.
PARIS fell away sharply in line with the trend among the late closing
markets with the CAC-40 index finishing just above the 1,900 support level
at 1,907.02, a decline of 32.00 for the session and 1.4 per cent for the
week. Turnover on the first day of the new account was estimated at some
FFr3.4bn.
In spite of the overall gloomy mood some bright spots could be found among
equities. Sanofi improved FFr38 to FFr853 in reaction to Thursday's news
that it was buying Sterling Winthrop's prescription drug business, while
some of the companies which have been forecasting better earnings prospects
also turned positive, St Gobain up FFr2 at FFr648 and Michelin adding
FFr6.70 at FFr221.50.
There was more bad news for Euro Disney, suspended limit down at one stage
before closing down FFr3.10 or 19 per cent at FFr12.90. There has been
considerable technical trading in the shares as doubts have grown about the
aftermath of the ongoing FFr6bn rights issue.
Elf Aquitaine slipped FFr14 to FFr390 as the group issued a profits warning.
ZURICH ended under renewed pressure. The SMI index fell through support at
the 2,580 level, losing 49.5 to 2,577.2, for a 1.9 per cent drop on the
week.
Cyclicals remained vulnerable, said Mr Frederick Hasslauer at Bank Sal
Oppenheim, to the threat of earnings revisions on the back of the weak
dollar. Sulzer lost SFr18 to SFr912 while Holderbank was SFr17 down at
SFr900.
Banks, which had earlier in the week halted their long slide, turned lower
again, losing an average of 1 per cent, although CS Holding fell SFr17 or
3.1 per cent to SFr535.
MILAN overcame early weakness as local investors covered positions ahead of
the weekend although the Comit index failed to register the late
improvement, losing 8.52 at 698.92, unchanged on the week.
Olivetti, however, was a bright spot, rising L45 to L2,455 following its
link with Hughes Network System to provide digital satellite communications
across Europe. CIR, the holding company, climbed L65 to L2,525.
Montedison gained another L22 or 1.5 per cent to L1,490 as investors
concentrated on its turnround potential.
MADRID reacted badly to the failure of dollar intervention, banks
particularly weak as the general index dropped 5.88, or 1.9 per cent to
299.14, 2.8 per cent lower on the week.
The exception in the banking sector, once again, was Bankinter, where
600,000 shares were put through the market, Bankinter itself buying from
Santander at Pta11,500 a share. The shares closed unchanged at Pta11,000.
Elsewhere, the decline took in construction, utilities and US favourites
like Repsol, down Pta125 at Pta3,870, but Telefonica showed relative
strength, easing just Pta15 to Pta1,760.
Brokers said that there was strong buying on the run-up to the placing of
Telefonica International.
AMSTERDAM was unsettled by the currencies turbulence with many of its
multinationals dependent on dollar earnings. The AEX index finished at the
session low of 381.43, down 5.95 on the day and 2.8 per cent on the week.
