<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / Markets Report: Support fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Central banks launched large scale co-ordinated intervention to support the
dollar but the US currency was unable to sustain brief gains, writes Motoko
Rich.
Taking their lead from the US Federal Reserve, a legion of central banks
repeatedly purchased the dollar in a move the markets had been anticipating
all week.
The dollar at first rallied after the intervention began in the European
afternoon, gaining more than a yen and about a pfennig and a half. But
although the Fed was still seen purchasing the US currency after 3:00 pm
GMT, the dollar lost most of its ground by the close of London trading.
The dollar ended in London at DM1.5972, down from DM1.6035. Against the yen,
it closed at Y100.900, down from Y101.150.
Analysts said the intervention had reinforced market cynicism about central
bank action. 'The intervention has been a miserable failure,' said Mr Tony
Norfield, UK treasury economist at ABN/AMRO bank. 'They have not scared off
any speculative trading.'
Although later denied, reported comments from Bank of Japan governor Yasushi
Mieno about the inability of intervention to 'dictate currency levels' kept
the markets bearish.
The dollar was lolling below Y100.50 and DM1.5950 when the Fed began the
concerted intervention around 1330 GMT by buying dollars for Y100.95. It
then followed about ten minutes later by buying the US currency for
DM1.6070/80. In the meantime, other central banks had also started to buy
the dollar.
As many as 17 central banks bought dollars in an effort similar to the group
action taken on May 4. The extent of the intervention was understood to be
between Dollars 2bn and Dollars 3bn, primarily from the Fed.
The central banks briefly turned sentiment towards the dollar, which rose to
a high of around DM1.61 and Y101.90. But the action failed to push the
dollar above key technical levels which analysts placed at DM1.6250 and
Y102.50.
'We have to see the intervention pushing the dollar to these key levels,'
said Mr Paul Chertkow, head of global currency research at UBS. 'Without
that we would expect the technical aspects of trading to remain bearish.'
Mr Chertkow said the central bank move came too late. 'If it had occured
last week when the pressure first began, then maybe it would have turned the
market,' he said.
Sterling had a banner day against the dollar, closing at Dollars 1.5422 from
Dollars 1.5386, and rising above the Dollars 1.55 level in after-hours
trading. Against the D-Mark, it closed in London at DM2.463, from DM2.4671.
A significant drop in the UK current account deficit for the first quarter
gave the pound a boost, while the ailing dollar gave sterling further
support.
In the UK money markets, the Bank of England provided liquidity of Pounds
159m after forecasting a revised shortage of Pounds 650m. The bank provided
late assistance of Pounds 390m.
In Europe, the D-Mark remained strong against the crosses. Against the
French franc, it closed in London at FFr3.425 from FFr3.422 and against the
lira, it closed at L984.6 from L982.6. Against the strong Swiss franc,
however, the D-Mark closed at SFr0.838, down from SFr0.842.
</TEXT>
