<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / Heseltine ready for postal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has resolved his
differences with the prime minister over the drafting of the green paper on
the future of the Post Office, now expected to be published next week,
Roland Rudd writes.
Mr John Major rejected the first draft, believing Mr Heseltine had not given
sufficient weight to the option of leaving the Post Office completely in the
public domain.
The Department of Trade and Industry believes its preferred option of
selling 51 per cent of the shares in Royal Mail and Parcelforce is still
given prominence over the other two options.
These are to make the Post Office more commercialised in the public sector
or to sell 49 per cent of the shares in Royal Mail and Parcelforce.
Mr Heseltine wants 10 per cent of the shares reserved for the workforce, the
maximum number allowed under Stock Exchange rules. He proposes a regulatory
structure aimed at strengthening rural services and uniform letter delivery.
