FT  25 JUN 94 / Tension foreseen on Dublin link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr James Molyneaux, leader of the Ulster Unionist party, will today
underline his party's opposition to joint authority between London and
Dublin over Northern Ireland's affairs.
He will use a speech in Larne to say joint authority would be 'a recipe for
increased instability and tension' and that the UUP is 'not prepared to
tolerate the establishment of the structures for the severance of the union
which joint authority would impose'.
In negotiations with Dublin, Britain is understood to have rejected any
suggestion that new north/south institutions could imply joint authority
over the province. It is prepared, however, to sanction cross-border
executive boards to oversee a common approach in some areas.
Whitehall officials are optimistic that the UUP will not reject such boards
out of hand. Their powers would be decided in consultation with the
constitutional parties.
Mr Molyneaux will say that his party wants the articles in the Irish
constitution enshrining Dublin's territorial claim over Ulster to be removed
 -'but not if it means selling the horse to buy a saddle'.
He will praise Mr Major as 'a prime minister who, more than any other since
the late 1960s, is prepared to listen to the parties and to act on their
advice.'
