<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / C&amp;W units in talks on AT&amp;T alliances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies controlled by Cable &amp; Wireless, the UK telecommunications group,
have been in talks with AT&amp;T, the largest US telecoms operator, about
forming an international alliance, despite C&amp;W claims that it is not
interested in such a tie-up.
Mercury, C&amp;W's UK subsidiary, drew back earlier this month from joining
AT&amp;T's Worldsource international partnership, in what an insider called a
'knife-edge' decision. However, Hongkong Telecom, C&amp;W's largest undertaking,
is still in talks and may soon join Worldsource.
C&amp;W's manoeuvring emerged as AT&amp;T announced an alliance with Unisource, the
venture between the Swedish, Dutch and Swiss national telecoms operators.
Unisource, of which Telefonica of Spain is an associate member, will take an
unspecified equity stake in Worldsource. It will market Worldsource-branded
products in Europe, geared to the growing market for one-stop international
telecoms services for multinational companies.
AT&amp;T's alliance is in fierce competition with two others launched in the
past year - a Dollars 5.3bn (Pounds 3.5bn) tie-up between British
Telecommunications and MCI, the second largest US operator; and a Dollars
4.2bn alliance, forged last week, between Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom,
and Sprint, the third largest US long-distance operator.
AT&amp;T had hoped to include Mercury in yesterday's announcement. Although the
UK operator would have become only an associate of Worldsource, the
concentration of multinationals in London made it attractive to AT&amp;T. Mr
Mike Harris, Mercury chief executive, said: 'There was a real problem in
getting into bed with AT&amp;T, given their existing international partners.'
KDD, the largest Japanese international operator, is an equity member of
Worldsource, and Telstra, the Australian national operator, an associate.
Both compete with operators in which C&amp;W holds stakes - IDC in Japan and
Optus in Australia - and those companies made representations to C&amp;W against
Mercury allying with AT&amp;T.
Mr John Tonroe, finance director of Hongkong Telecom, in which C&amp;W has a
57.5 per cent stake, said the company was open to joining Worldsource,
denying that C&amp;W would veto such a move. Mr Harris acknowledged that
Hongkong Telecom might adopt a different strategy to the rest of C&amp;W.
Mr Robert Morris, analyst at Goldman Sachs, said: 'C&amp;W really does have a
dilemma about how it fits into the emerging international alliances.'
Lex, Page 20; AT&amp;T's hidden global agenda, Page 26
</TEXT>
