<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When selling resumed in Australia on Tuesday prices generally were firm to
unchanged. A slightly easier tendency appeared the next day, but by Thursday
prices were again firm. However, the real test of values will come next
week, at the closing sales for the 1993-94 season, when there will be
substantial quantities of wool on offer. It is noted that there has been a
fall of inquiry for stockpile wool. Last week's sales, reports Wool
International, totalled 4,687 bales, of which 3,418 were for deferred
delivery. At June 17 the stockpile amounted to 3,678,788 bales. While most
traders continue to predict a reasonably firm start to next season's sales,
a key factor in the longer term is the reluctance of spinners to pay prices
for tops which fully reflect current replacement costs. The market indicator
was 627c/kg on Thursday.
</TEXT>
