<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / International Company News: Labatt lifted by strong brewing
operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
John Labatt, one of Canada's two largest brewers, said new products helped
to push beer sales up 4 per cent to CDollars 389m (USDollars 278m) in the
fourth quarter ended April 30, and up 6 per cent to CDollars 1.8bn for the
full year.
Operating profit rose 19 per cent for the year to CDollars 260m, with
Canadian brewing operations leading the way.
However, the US operations also did well, showing 18 per cent growth in
volume and benefiting from removal of the tariff on Ontario beer exports to
the US last August.
In Europe, Birra Moretti's operating results improved and UK sales rose
sharply with inclusion of pub revenues.
Since the year end, Labatt has added 168 pubs, bringing the total to more
than 500 in England and Wales.
The broadcasting, sports and entertainment group posted a 15 per cent gain
in sales for the year, but operating profit slipped because of losses in an
entertainment unit.
Overall, Labatt reported consolidated fourth-quarter net profit from
continuing operations of CDollars 28m, or 26 cents a share, up from CDollars
9m, or 5 cents, a year earlier on total revenues of CDollars 516m, up 16 per
cent.
For the full year, net profit was CDollars 155m, or CDollars 1.53 a share,
up 17 per cent from CDollars 133m, or CDollars 1.32, in 1993.
Sales were CDollars 2.3bn, up 9 per cent.
The year-earlier period excluded special charges taken mainly for the
writedown of Labatt's US dairy business to net realisable value.
