<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Thorn EMI sells part of defence side to
French
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thorn EMI, the rental and music group, said yesterday it had agreed in
principle to sell part of its defence activities to Thomson-CSF, the French
defence electronics group.
The deal, while not unexpected, amounts to a significant step in the
consolidation of the European defence industry, where pressure to merge has
been growing because of falling defence procurement budgets.
Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Turnover of the activities sold, which
include missile-fusing systems and electro-optics, was about Pounds 80m last
year. Some 1,100 people work in the division affected, which is based at
Hayes in Middlesex.
Thomson-CSF is already a strong player in electro-optics, while the Thorn
unit it is now acquiring expects to do lucrative work providing thermal
imaging and infra-red systems for the European Fighter Aircraft.
The deal leaves out Thorn's defence electronics activity in three other
centres - Crawley, Wells and Rugeley - whose combined sales were about
Pounds 110m last year.
However a company spokesman said it was still hoped to dispose of those
businesses. 'As it is our strategy to concentrate on the music and rental
sectors, we will continuing to looking new homes for the remaining defence
electronics businesses,' he said.
The Crawley unit provides electronic support systems such as radar and
jamming devices for ships and aircraft, and analysts said the British
government would look carefully at any deal which let this business fall
into foreign hands.
MoD officials have said they have no objection to foreign interests taking
equity stakes and earning dividends from British defence companies.
</TEXT>
